The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 World Briefs

 Dhaka airport shut 

 Dhaka, Feb. 11 (Reuters): Bangladeshs main international airport was closed today after several wheels burst on a Boeing 747 as it attempted to take-off. 

 The Saudi Arabian Airlines flight with nearly 400 people on board was forced to abort its take-off for Riyadh and return to the terminal buildings. Airport officials said efforts were being put to clear the airports single runway. 

 Harvard boss 

 Cambridge (AP): Harvard University on Sunday prepared to name Civil War historian Drew Gilpin Faust as its 28th and first woman president. Faust, a noted scholar of the American South and dean of Harvards Radcliffe Institute of Advanced Study, would succeed the tumultuous five-year tenure of Lawrence Summers. 

 Abortion poll 

 Lisbon (Reuters): Portugal voted on Sunday on whether to legalise abortion that could bring the Catholic country into line with most European states. Opinion polls showed a majority in favour of making abortion legal in the first 10 weeks of pregnancy. 

 Iraq violence 

 Baghdad (AP): A suicide truck bomber slammed into a crowd of police lining up for duty on Sunday near Tikrit, killing at least 30 people. Minutes later, a roadside bomb killed two others. 




